problems.description: For this problem, place the value 2.5 in the variable x and 2 in the variable y.
problems.examples: Numbers can be be stored in more than one way. They can be integers like 1, 2 or 3 or they can be floating-point (real) numbers such as 1.0, 2.3, and 3.5. When you divide an integer by an integer, you usually get an integer. When you divide an integer by a double (floating-point number), or a double by a double, or a double by an integer, you get a double.
problems.name: Double

problems.description: When you want to raise one number to the power of another number you have to use the pow method from the Math class. Place the value 27 in the variable x.
problems.examples: For example Math.pow(2,3) = 8.0 since 2 to the power of 3 is 8. Note that the pow method returns a double.
problems.name: Exponentiation

problems.description: When you want a float as a response, make sure that either the numerator or the denominator are a float. Put the value 0.2 in the variable x and the value 1 in to the variable y.
problems.examples: Sometimes dividing integers in Java can produce an response that you might not expect. For example: 1 / 2 does not evaluate to 0.5. Instead it evaluates to 0 since both 1 and 2 are integers. This can be confusing at times.
problems.name: Integer Division

problems.description: You can use parenthesis ( ) to specify which mathematical operations should take place first. Place the number 19 in the variable x.
problems.examples: For example: 5 + 3 * 2 = 11 because the multiplication takes place first. However, (5 + 3 ) * 2 = 16 since the parenthesis cause the addition to take place prior to the multiplication.
problems.name: Order of Operations

problems.description: Assign the string "gonow" to the variable x and "nownow" to the variable y.
problems.examples: You cannot perform most mathematical operations on strings. For example: "hello" / "hi" would not make much sense. However, you can concatenate, or add strings together ("hi" + "bob" = "hibob"). Note, however, that Java does _not_ allow the multiplication of strings by an integer ("hi" * 3 gives an error, not "hihihi").
problems.name: String operations

problems.description: Try to place the value 9 in the variable x by adding other numbers and variables to x.
problems.examples:
You can add a number to a variable and assign the result to the original variable using the +=  operator. For example: x += 2 is the same as x = x + 2.
You have to declare x as an integer (and optionally give it a starting value) before you can use it.
problems.name: Plus Equal

problems.description: Try to place the value "Hello world" in the variable greeting by adding other strings to greeting.
problems.examples: You can add a string to a variable and assign the result to the original variable using the +=  operator. For example: x += " world" is the same as x = x + " world". You have to declare greeting as a String (and optionally give it a starting value) before you can use it.
problems.name: Plus Equal String

problems.description: You can subtract a number from a variable and assign the result to the original variable using the -=  operator. Try to place the value 1 in the variable x by subtracting other numbers and variables from x.
problems.examples: For example: x -= 2 is the same as x = x - 2. You have to declare x as an integer (and optionally give it a starting value) before you can use it.
problems.name: Minus Equal

problems.description: You can multiply a variable times a number and assign the result to the variable using the *=  operator. Try to place the value 16 in the variable x by multiplying x by other numbers.
problems.examples: For example: x *= 2 is the same as x = x * 2. You have to declare x as a numeric data type (and optionally give it a starting value) before you can use it.
problems.name: Times Equal

problems.description: You can divide a variable by a number and assign the result to the variable using the /=  operator. Try to place the value 3 in the variable x by dividing x by other numbers.
problems.examples: For example: x /= 2 is the same as x = x / 2. You have to declare x as a numeric data type (and optionally give it a starting value) before you can use it.
problems.name: Divide Equal
